 A rough crossing indeed. And one that changes you, in subtle ways that I have yet to grasp a full understanding.<br>
<br>
 I arrived, disoriented, almost unable to move and speak, in the grounds of a Tower named Lethantis...a place where sorcery was regularly woven, I was later to discover, and where the veil between worlds was thin enough to let me through... <br>
<br>
 I collapsed amongst the trees, struggling for breath in the alien air... I may have perished there if not for the aid of a kind passerby - he was a young man, tall and thin, with pure white hair tied back in a ponytail. He saw my distress and helped me to my feet, guiding me toward the nearby tower...<br>
<br>
 The mages of Lethantis took me in at this stanger's behest, and nursed me back to health...perhaps more out of scientific curiosity than compassion...<br>
<br>
 Anyway, within the week, I had regained my senses enough to speak and walk, and even affect a few minor magics under the tution of the curious mages.<br>
<br>
 Here is where my greatest pain lies. Every night I tried to commune with the source of my power, to draw strength from the elemental force of the Stormbringer, Karana... yet to no avail. I could not summon a candle flame, let alone an Elemental.<br>
<br>
 Whether this was due to my lack of faith, or the barrier of the void between worlds, I know not...Karana could not hear me, and I could not reach him. I was almost powerless...<br>
<br>
 Yet I had my Will. The power of 45 seasons of Magecraft still burned in my mind. I found I could move small objects with concentrated thought...that I could make minor manipulations of the essence of this realm through Willpower alone...<br>
<br>
 The mages of Lethantis guided me down this path they called Sorcery...and began my training there as an Apprentice.<br>
<br>
 I was soon to meet Ezmeres, and Grymwyll, and later become an Initiate of the Order of the Old Code...<br>
<br>
 But still I need to find and thank the young man who saved me on my first night in Albion...I remember him saying his name was Slainthe...a squire in the service of Lord Adribard...<br>
<br>
 If you see him, tell him I am grateful.<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------<br>
